text: Although I was anticipating the release of this film, I was disappointed after researching some information about Mr. Nate Parker. Not only was he accused of raping a female college student in 1999 at Penn State (which by no means is proclamation of guilt, but is nonetheless shocking and leaves one scratching their head), he has made it clear that he will never play a "gay character." He has also taken the liberty to discuss the "emasculation and feminization of the black male" in film and television, expressing concern "to preserve the black man" in media. However, he has played a gang member in the past ("Red Hook Summer") and appears to have a non-black wife (not that there is anything wrong with this, but it is relevant to a discussion about black identity, images, and manhood/masculinity).  What does this have to do with this "Birth of A Nation" film, you ask? Well first, for someone so committed to telling the story of an African American man that risked his life for his freedom and the freedom of others, it seems a little close-minded, bigoted, and reductive to never consider playing a "gay character." Afterall, an actor or actress should have range and challenge him or herself to play characters that may be different from one's own self, especially those that are marginalized or have stories that haven't been told, right? Why completely shut the idea out without having more information about a potential progressive story in which playing a "gay character" may be of interest?  Second, what exactly is his "image" of the black male that needs to be "preserved?" I hope it has nothing to do with being violent, overly hostile, sexually aggressive toward women, or only desiring women that have European features. Afterall, what constitutes an "image of a black male" in this society is subjective and isn't a one-size-fits-all description.   Third, in a discussion about images of the "black male," women (both black and of other races) usually can be connected to the conversation in some way. The right for Mr. Parker to have a fair-skinned or white wife is his; however, to single out and call in question the image of the black male and "those with questionable sexuality" as being an issue of "emasculation" is somewhat hypocritical and one-sided. If interracial love/marriage is okay (and it is!!!) and isn't emasculating or somehow doesn't devalue the 'blackness' or 'manhood' of the black man, then why must his sexuality? I'm certain Mr. Parker knows better than this. Also, when discussing slavery and black history, relationships between black men and non-black women have (historically) been a point of contention for many (which is another discussion entirely but can be extended from the current conversation).     Fourth, since he has been on the receiving end of a rape allegation in the past, I think he should also offer an impassioned opinion on rape culture on college campuses - especially since it seems to be a valid issue in 2016 (just my opinion). This would be a great opportunity to discuss how masculinity and patriarchy have been used to promote passivity of sexual assaults against women.         The point? Being selective in one's liberation or advocacy for characters with stories shouldn't be based on bigoted or prejudiced ideals. One's own liberation shouldn't disregard the liberation of others. The Nat Turner story is one of dignity, strength, courage, and equality ON A HUMAN LEVEL. The character of the man producing/re-introducing such a narrative project is relevant. You cannot uplift the triumphs of one man or woman while discounting and devaluing those of others, especially when there are stark commonalities within the human condition. People are people. Period. Gay, straight, black, white, male female, whatever. Everyone has story and no story should be devalued. Although Mr. Parker is entitled to select and play the characters he wants, his reasoning behind such should not aim to trivialize and reduce the lives of some or to reinforce the bigotry plaguing our society.

text: 1. This movie actually seems well-made... People complain that this is yet another slave movie, but this seems to take a different approach to it. Kind of like an infinitely better Free State of Jones in a slave viewpoint.  2. Black Lives Matter     Asian Lives Matter     Latino Lives Matter    Yes.... Even White Lives Matter    Everyone's Life Matters. To the people who clicked on this trailer and thought this movie was going to be great, ok. To the people who clicked on this trailer and thought this movie was going to be clich√®, ok. Congratulations on forming original thoughts and becoming a rational human being! But to judge a movie based on racial tensions or the fact that an individual has preference to one race or another is completely inappropriate or inaccurate. Yes, people have the right to learn about our history, and it is crucial that we should (in reference to George Orwell's 1984) in order to improve our society. HOWEVER, individuals also have the right to recognize certain patterns and state that they exist. Which brings me to my next point.  3. Slave movies are oftentimes excellent, but there is no doubt that some movies are made for Oscar bait. It is just a common fact. For example, The Butler. A sappy, easily forgetful movie starring Forest Whitaker about a butler who lives through eras in history. The only reason that movie existed was because it had what once was the Oscar movie formula: historical events, racial tensions/handicaps, happy ending. And the list continues. The Curious Case of Benjamin Button: all white cast, for the most part. Basically a rip-off of Forrest Gump: handicapped man falls in love with a woman and must try to set aside his differences in order to live a normal life. The only reason it was admitted into the Oscars was because it had the SAME OSCAR MOVIE FORMULA. This doesn't stop at race, it transcends that. So, there are some slave movies that were made NOT for the benefit of the people, but for the benefit of fame.  4. Finally, to those who ask themselves publicly if they have to feel white guilt, what kind of a question is that? Are you a racist? Are you considered of the white race and are you a proven bigoted racist? If so, then no, you do not have to feel white guilt. I agree that white men and women have disgraced the African-American population over history, but that is no reason to seek revenge on others because of what happened in the past. Everyone talks of equality, but if an individual is going to say, "Hey, you remember that thing your dead great grandfather did? We're just going to remind you of it, rub it in your face, and verbally abuse you and your family for all eternity." That, ladies and gentleman, is thinking backwards. How are we going to coincide if all there is is hate? Are the descendants from Constantinople still holding a grudge against the Turks who invaded? Are all the descendants from Russia still angry that Napoleon invaded their country, and are now taking revenge against them? No. Because it is history. We learn it, but we do not misuse it because times are always changing. Although, if you are white/latino/asian/african-american/etc. and have said or done something racist, then ignore this message. Because you should feel guilt. And learn from it. And forgive. And be forgiven. And move on.

text: You can say what you want about this film, but it isn't a made up story. It's history. It's fact. This happened. There's no denying that. So to criticize the movie for something the people it portrays did is foolish. Not to mention Nat Turner wasn't even a bad man for what he did. He may have gone about it the wrong way but what can you do when you are an imprisoned slave? Not every slave can be like Frederick Douglass and escape safely. People like Nat Turner. People like John Brown. They were necessary in order to help push forth the freedom these people needed. Both Turner and Brown had their flaws in their actions. But the message they portrayed is what mattered. And in the end, it was an actual war that ended slavery. It took violence to end violence for one time of many in history. In the end we learned from it though. And the world has changed for the better. Not everything is sunshine and rainbows and racism was and still is an ideology that unfortunately exists. We learn about it to prevent it from happening again. So whatever criticism you can have of this movie, know that it is history, not lie.
